        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Charleston, S. C.</placeName>
                <date>April 15. 5619</date>.</p>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Is. Leeser</addressee>, <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Altho' I have but<lb/> very little time before <add>שבת</add>, yet,
                anxious to have the <hi rend="underline">status</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">quo ante bellum</hi> restored before that holy day, I will
                reply<lb/> at once, even in but few lines.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Not accustomed to boast of what I do in the
                <sic>fulfilment</sic><lb/> of what I deem my duty, I never told you, that I <hi
                    rend="underline">did</hi><lb/> write to <persName>Dr Philippson</persName>
                concerning your <sic>defence</sic> against the<lb/> slanderous attacks of the author
                of the “Tkizzin<add>?</add>”, and made<lb/> my commentary upon his (<persName>Dr
                    Ph's</persName>.) silence. But the Doctor<lb/> neither published my letter, nor
                made even the slightest<lb/> mention of it in several of his epistles to me. This
                man<lb/> one of the reasons why I broke off all official connection<lb/> with the
                Zeitung des Judenthums. You may be assured, I<lb/> spoke very plainly &amp; bluntly
                to him. Nor did I stop there.<lb/> In a letter to <persName>Stein's</persName>
                    “<add>?</add>” (published in No 4,<lb/>
                <date>1858</date>, p. 135-136), I alluded to the injustice done us by the
                Z.d.J.,<lb/> and stated that the author of the “Tkizzin,” was nothing<lb/> less than
                    “<add>?</add><lb/>
                <add>?</add>”; but what was the consequence? <persName>Dr Ph.</persName><lb/> &amp;
                    <persName>Mr. Eppstein</persName>, now sojourning in
                    <placeName>Breslaw</placeName>, kept<lb/> silent, and that was the last of that
                affair. Could I<lb/> do more? It was my intention, &amp; <persName>Stein</persName>
                knew it, to get</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>either <persName>Dr P.</persName> or <persName>Mr. Eppstein</persName> into a
                controversy with me upon that<lb/> topic; but they preferred to “<hi
                    rend="underline">show no light</hi>.” From all this you<lb/> must now perceive
                that I have “seconded you in your endeavor<lb/> to have justice done to you,” &amp;
                trust you will now in justice to me <del>?</del><lb/> reconsider your remark:
                    <del>but in</del> “in this too I<lb/> feel disappointed,” as your conclusion was
                certainly an incor-<lb/>rect one. I do not blame you for it; the fault lies in
                my<lb/> silence. But I beg you, once for all, to be assured, that I<lb/> am
                incapable of doing injustice to any one; nothing can<lb/> mortify me more than to
                have injustice done to me, &amp;, therefore,<lb/> I always act according to
                    <persName>Hillel's</persName> maxim: <add>מה דעלך סני וגו'</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As I had ordered but <hi rend="underline">one</hi> Bible, I kept
                one, and<lb/> handed the other to <persName>Mr. Hart</persName> &amp; took his
                receipt for the<lb/> same.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This must suffice for to-day—<add>שבת</add> is<lb/> coming fast upon
                me, so good <add>שבת</add>, yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">Dr M Mayer</persName>
            </p>
            <p>The little letter to <persName>Mr. Hart</persName><lb/> has been delivered.</p>
        </body>
